<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-7057842244450392366'>
<p>
It seems to me our argument here is futile. <br /><br />I prefer VS but have programmed using Eclipse, XCode and a half dozen other IDEs great and small.<br /><br />I consider myself a hardcore C++ developer but I also use Java and since 2005 Objective-C regularly and take pleasure in developing in other languages every chance I get.<br /><br />Everyone here with any experience at all will have a similar story substituting there personal experiences.<br /><br />IMHO, we are here arguing because, hate it or love it, Apple has provided a great platform, a great set of development tools/libraries, and a great market place. Great enough to bring players from other platforms to develop for and scrutinize. <br /><br />I remember having/reading the same types of arguments around C++ , Java and its earlier IDEs, Qt, .NET, SOA, Web 2.0 and other technologies/computer languages. Thank god for variation. We would other wise have nothing interesting to talk about.<br /><br />You gotta love it. Oh and long live zealotry etc....<br /><br /><i>Yes, this is the same post I made on Lamarche&#39;s blog</i>
</p>
