<dt class='comment-author ' id='c4146335806259184364'>
<a name='c4146335806259184364'></a>
<div class="avatar-image-container avatar-stock"><span dir="ltr"><a href="http://www.blogger.com/profile/05862497628924727350" rel="nofollow" onclick="" class="avatar-hovercard" id="av-65-05862497628924727350"><img src="http://img2.blogblog.com/img/b16-rounded.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Adam Smith">

</a></span></div>
<a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/05862497628924727350' rel='nofollow'>Adam Smith</a>
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-4146335806259184364'>
<p>
Interesting comments. But as you say yourself it does show your bias from working so long with java. <br /><br />A lot of your negative comments (e.g. about how to use the IDE, lots of open Windows etc) just show inexperience with working with Mac software in general and xCode in particular.<br /><br />While Objective-C is often quite verbose, I find that for larger applications Java requires you to do a lot more typing. In java you end up having to subclass and define interfaces all the time, where in Objective-C you just send a message. <br /><br />The dynamic nature of Objective-C can save you a lot of code. Implementing something like delegating in Java is going to require a lot more code than in Objective-C.<br /><br />I agree the .m and .h file separation and #import is old fashion compared to Java. But I still think a lot of the flexibility from the dynamic nature of Objective-C makes up for a lot of short comings in other areas where Java has an edge. And let us not forget the ability to seamlessly integrate C and C++ code
</p>
</dd>
