<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-6329742370601492734'>
<p>
i read this article before starting iphone development about a year ago - i just stumbled across it again, and re-read it. I have to say, most of this article says more about how difficult and weird iphone development is, but little about how efficient and enjoyable it can be once you are proficient at it.<br /><br />I just started android dev, and I&#39;m back to being confused, frustrated, and wishing I could go back to iPhone dev (despite being a 12 year java dev). <br /><br />So, it really is what you&#39;re used to - i&#39;d love to see a follow up article from someone who&#39;s spent a good chunk of time with both environments and understand why XCode/Cocoa/Obj-C are the way they are and the oddities of android dev (for e.g. nowhere is it mentioned that the android emulator takes anywhere from 30s to 2m to install and run a simple app).<br /><br />In my estimation, iphone, with its cocoa history is by far the more mature platform and SDK.
</p>
