<p>
I am really surprised with this article as someone who has much experience in java and almost none on Objective C dare to compare those two languages and platforms.<br />I have a lot of experience in developing applications on C++, Objective C.<br />What I was struggling about this article is to pick from tit how much experience the writer has on developing with xCode and Apple dev tools and as well probably no experience (at least not serious one) with Objective C and mobile development. <br />Firs if you are talking about two platforms which you use to develop mobile application you must know some things about mobile and embedded development first. <br />You are glorifying garbage collection on mobile device? First Garbage Collection takes too much time for processing and do not forget that you are developing for device 100 time slower then your slowest desktop (CPU520Mhz with 256MB of RAM). Mobile device does not have so many resources so having garbage collection is not an option. By the way if you use Objective C for MAC and Cocoa dev then you can use garbage collection as it is available on the framework but it is not available on iPhone SDK for a reason.<br />Knowing the memory allocation and language internals (compiler as well) will not give you headache for memory management. If you learn reference counting internals and just simple Get, Copy and Alloc rules you&#39;ll be absolutely fine with when the function returns the ownership and when not (and thats it only for the API of the SDK it self as with your own classes you can do what you like). But as you used to use garbage collection your perception of the memory allocation is completely different so do not compare this two things at all.<br />Why I got impression that you do not have serious experience of Objective C is that you are complaining why you have alloc and init in combination. If you read docs you will find that there is construction<br />NSObject* obj = [[NSObject alloc] init];<br />and<br />NSObject* obj = [NSObject new];<br /><br />These two constructions are the same my friend.<br /><br />You said it is language of 80&#39;s. So I would really like to here a bit of explanations here WHY. What Java brings to the market which is so modern that Objective C does not. If you speak about protocol in development it self I must tell you that Objective C has totally different approach to development so you cannot compare it with Java. Especially as it is dynamic language (Java is static like C++) and you can do so many powerful things in the runtime like (adding new methods to the class in runtime, posing classes if you know what does it mean and a lot of other useful thing which you cannot do with Java or not in so elegant way like in Obj C).<br /><br />To be continued in next post.
</p>
