</dt>
<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-9203132204557548290'>
<p>
From your example I can see that you do not have much experience in using getters and setters properly as you are not using it properly like an advance developer. Let me show you what I am talking about:<br /><br />Server.h should be<br /><br />@interface Server : Updatable <br />{<br />@private // as you want to hide the real storage from user of this class<br />NSString* _name;  &lt;-- declare the property <br />}<br /><br />@property (nonatomic,retain) NSString *name; &lt;--- declare the property again<br />@end<br /><br />Server.m should be:<br /><br />@synthesize name = _name;  &lt;-- implement getter/setter<br /><br />-(void) dealloc <br />{<br />   //[name release];  &lt;-- THIS IS WRONG AS YOU SUPPOSE TO USE SETTER FOR THIS<br />   self.name = nil; // Much safer<br />}<br /><br />what will happen if you did in a code [name release]; without NULL-ing it. In your dealloc it will bomb as you will try to use the pointer which is corrupted. With mine construction self.name = nil you are always safe.<br /><br />THis is a simple basic use and from this I can see that you do not know the basics of memory management as I can expect it if you are used to use garbage collection for a years and do not bother whats going on under a hood.<br /><br />In mobile dev everything is about a speed. So doing things properly will bring a boost to the application.<br /><br />Use this link (http://cocoawithlove.com/2008/12/instance-variable-to-synthesized.html) to automate the getters/setters in xCode from IDE. <br /><br />You mention so many things about Objective C which are not true as you saying Objective C is an old platform. So how old Java is then?<br />Docs is really good if you know how to use it from xCode. Class organisation is really simple and you can find in docs inheritance tree. But if you know the iPhone SDK (like you do java) you will not be bothered with the question of which method to use and from which class. Now you do as you do not have enough experience with it and you are probably at the beginning of the learning curve so it is expected.<br /><br />Comparing Eclipse and xCode. <br />Do you want to tell me that docs are not integrated in xCode (if you do like you did in your post then you are wrong). Use alt + mouse click on any message and it brings the assistant or you can enable Quick help and it will show you the help in the docs for messages as you type.<br />Second you cannot compare Java with Objective C as java is not compiling in binary code like Objective C does so compile process for Objective C and C like languages are slightly different then java as they do not need VM. So do not compare that.<br />There is a refactoring in xCode but obviously you do not know how to use it.<br />If you do not like many windows why didn&#39;typiu set All-in-One in xCode so you can with one mouse click set your look of IDe for dev or debug without opening new window. What about splitting window on two and see one file on left / top and another on right / bottom. What about small icons on the right part of the window where you can use many options available for your current file and class you are working on. You need a serious lecture for xCode. <br />Not able to change values in debigger in xCode is not true. YOU CAN DO IT MATE. If you have a pointer and want to se a detail just place your cursor on top of the variable name and after a sec it will offer you a small window where you can use disclosure button to open for details. The sam in debugger variable pane.<br /><br />I am tired of typing so I must give you a suggestion. Before you do a serious dev on a new platform and try to write a comparision like this be sure you have learned an things or two about it.<br /><br />Cheers<br />Syberglitch
</p>
