<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-8789105557298388105'>
<p>
@syberglitch Thanks for your comments and suggestions.  A few of points you make are worthy of some attention:<br /><br />Regarding garbage collection: though you may be right in that garbage collection adds to processing overhead, the extent to which this is true depends entirely on the implementation.  Ruling it out due to platform limitations is just plain wrong.  Garbage collection is used successfully in mobile devices, as demonstrated by the Android platform.  My point is that memory management code obscures application logic.<br /><br />I agree that Objective-C is powerful and has some great language features.  What I take issue with is the cumbersome syntax and weak IDE support.<br /><br />Regarding dealloc and releasing instance variables, you may be interested to see this quote from Apple&#39;s book <i>The Objective-C 2.0 Programming Language</i>:<br />Typically in a dealloc method you should release object instance variables directly (rather than invoking a set accessor and passing nil as the parameter)<br /><br />You missed the point about documentation integration in the IDE.  With thousands of apis it&#39;s impossible to know it all, no matter how experienced you are.<br /><br />You&#39;re right about the all-in-one mode.  It&#39;s too bad it&#39;s not the default setting.<br /><br />I&#39;m not sure if you noticed: I did say many good things about the Apple/iPhone side as well!<br /><br />Thanks again for your comments.
</p>
</dd>
