<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-794388697150660285'>
<p>
As I am aware of Android platform is that when garbage collection kicks in all the UI stuff are frozen until its finished so using garbage collection you must be really carefull about how many objects you are allocating at the time.<br />Second in ObjC you have one really useful thing as Auto Release Pools. You can make and instance of your class as autoreleased which will be released on next Run loop event (which can be UI event). So there you are something similar (not like GC but useful). The only think you have to be careful about the lifetime of the object. But simple if you want to take an ownership just do retain on it and you will be responsible of destroying it. So memory management is simple.<br />The GC is not on iPhone simple just as it should not be on any embedded device not because of device limitation.<br />I do not think that memory management obscure application logic. The whole thing is about it. Playing with memory management can bring you many powerful things. So many designs in app development relays on it (especially on embedded devices where you suppose to save as much memory as you can so how to do it if your not handling it). I do agree with you that in many occasions you can shoot your self in the foot if you are not careful but you can do that with GC as well. The thing is that what its says in docs for dealloc is not what I suggested you. As depends on how did you declare your property.<br />If its retain then null-ing it is the same as releasing it but it is safer as after it release it it just null-s it (which developers forgot in most cases). Nulling the pointer in destructor is not needed but is a good programming practice. To give you an example of retain setter<br /><br />@property (monatomic, retain) id setterForVar; <br /><br />when its compiled is converted to this<br /><br />- (void)setterForVar:(id)value<br />{<br />  // If value is null nothing happens<br />  [value retain];<br />  // this is the same as you would do it manually<br />  [setterForVar release];<br />  // here if value is null we simple null the pointer<br />  setterForvar = value;<br />}<br /><br />to be continued in next post
</p>
</dd>
