<p>
I saw so many bugs because someone forgot to null the pointer. So my advice is if you have property for your var use it and do not release it in the class code so often as it is bug prone. Use setter as it is safer.<br />Another thing with GC is that it can happen in many occasions that you have object which is not needed by anyone and it is still there in memory occupying valuable space just because GC did not kicked in yet. Then my question to you is multithreading and GC? Think about that as well. I agree with you as GC wipe away all your problems with the memory but it brings a lot of overhead as you mentioned as well and certainly uses more resources then without it. <br />Why you are afraid of memory management. I herd this from many java developers. There is a big possibility for every  one not using GC to do a bad things but we should not be afraid of development as if someone afraid of driving the car it does not drives it as there is a possibility to crash.<br />Application logic is not about memory management. Application logic is about your class relationship and data passing one to each other. About who is responsible of what. When you do an UML design for you app you are not using memory management at all and probably you are not think about it. If you compare two platforms then you suppose to have completely different approach as a developer. By the way do not let the tool to choose your app for development do it opposite. Design app and then choose a tool.<br /><br />About docs. I did not missed the point as thousands of apis at=re there for Android as well and Java as well. So what is a difference. If you are know what you are looking for then it is fast. For me (and I have many, many years of experience on mac with ObjC, Coco and iPhone) and I did not spend more then 5 min to find what I am looking for. If you want to do something and you do not know what to search for then you must know which part of the api you are using (is it graphics, audio, video, UI control or what) then narrow your search with the category.<br /><br />Do not get me wrong as I did not want to criticise so much the only think is that I found many things in your blog which were not true.<br /><br />By the way I have more then 17 years of experience in C, C++, Assembler, more then 5 years in ObjC (I really do not know how many years) and about 10 years in embedded development of which is 5 years in mobile industry. Currently I am developing apps for iPhone, Symbian and Android for the last 4 years mainly.<br /><br />Cheers<br />Dejan
