<dt class='comment-author ' id='c1433708528930401282'>
<a name='c1433708528930401282'></a>
<div class="avatar-image-container avatar-stock"><span dir="ltr"><img src="http://img1.blogblog.com/img/blank.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Steven Noyes">

</span></div>
Steven Noyes
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-1433708528930401282'>
<p>
It is interesting to see the difference experience in tools sets makes.  In my case, I come from 10+ years of C/C++/Objective C heavy in the embedded when doing C/C++.  Java will never fly in the industry I tend to work in and so really do not know it well.<br /><br />So when going to do some iPhone development, I found the IDE simple, clean and completely worked with me.<br /><br />At the same time, when I went to do some simple Android work (just for fun), I found the Eclipse based IDE felt like something from the &#39;90&#39;s.  The Java class organization random and the Java string handling poorly thought out and frustrating to find the functionality I needed.   Accessing docs was a RPITA.  Working with Eclipse felt like getting a root canal every day.  But then, I do not have years of experience working with Java or Eclipse.  However, after 3 weeks of use, I can guarantee you that Eclipse will never be my developer tool set of choice.  OK, on a project for the past 2 years,Eclipse was the &quot;default&quot; IDE.  I gave it a month and then said by-by; so I was not totally new to Eclipse.<br /><br />Likewise, there were many problems with your understanding of Objective-C IMO (Just as I am not that familiar with Java and I am sure the string classes are fine)  for example, int init methods you can:<br /><br />- (id) initWithName:(NSString *) newName<br />{<br />    if (self = [super init])<br />    {<br />        [self setName:newName];<br />        return self;<br />    }<br />}<br /><br />There are no issues with calling the accessor methods in either the init or the dealloc routines.   This all depends, of course, on your design of KVO and such.  Likewise, if you have notifications setup in accessors, you need be able to handle nil objects passed to their observers.  Personally, I always design this way so using accessors in init and dealloc work to my advantage.  I find that overuse of accessors causes substantially less issues than underuse so I use them almost exclusively.
</p>
</dd>
