<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-2039217929162397330'>
<p>
I&#39;ve been a developer for 14 years, and currently work as a technical architect and get the opportunity to work with many different platforms and APIs. <br /><br />Compared to Objective C, Java definitely sets a lower bar for entry. As I cut my teeth on C++ and Pascal, I wouldn&#39;t say that is a result of a bias towards Java, just an objective look at what it took to get up and running (productive) with it.<br /><br />That said, I would not say that the reason Objective C isn&#39;t as developer friendly as Java is because of some deficiency. Java does a lot more work for the developer, which generally results in code that performs less consistently, particularly in graphically intensive applications. <br /><br />As someone who spends a great deal of time in application architecture, I agree with the merits of GC in returning the focus of development to application logic as opposed to logistics, and has non-trivial returns in terms of productivity. But, the reality is that it is also often a license for poorly written applications, as the platform will scramble to fix all of a developer&#39;s &quot;mistakes&quot;. Apple places this burden on the developer, which is actually the right call for a mobile platform (not necessarily my opinion for desktop or web, though...)<br /><br />The bottom line is that Apple had created the largest mobile app consumer market on the planet before anyone even knew what an &quot;app&quot; was, so was never any need to coax developers into picking it up. They can keep the bar high which in turn results in an overall higher quality assortment of apps to choose from. Android is playing the role of the underdog, and their philosophy seems to be that in order to quickly produce a large selection of apps, the developer experience needs to be enticing. As another poster commented, this will probably mean that a stink will develop around the Android apps as a result. I&#39;ve managed teams of outsourced Java developers, and have seen the abandon of best practices, reasonable documentation, and conventions of any sort that are at least enabled by an intelligent IDE, managed code, and high-level languages. Apple seems to go to greater lengths to protect the end user from the middling developer (it kind of aligns with their hardware philosophy).<br /><br />I do agree with some of the gripes about XCode, though. You can say that it boils down to which platform you have more experience with, but when you look throughout recent history at the most popular IDEs - Visual Studio, Eclipse, CodeGear, etc - while they all have personality differences, XCode out of the box stands out as the complete oddball, and it&#39;s not unreasonable for a developer to be turned off by it.
</p>
</dd>
