<dt class='comment-author ' id='c8311106701860182365'>
<a name='c8311106701860182365'></a>
<div class="avatar-image-container avatar-stock"><span dir="ltr"><img src="http://img1.blogblog.com/img/blank.gif" width="16" height="16" alt="" title="Anonymous">

</span></div>
Anonymous
said...
</dt>
<dd class='comment-body' id='Blog1_cmt-8311106701860182365'>
<p>
Hi,<br /><br />Just stumble upon this post from last year. I think many of the opinion against memory management and favor GC is not accurate.<br /><br />I have worked with C/C++ embedded system for 10 years and most of the work I&#39;ve done are on systems with executable size of &lt;1MB and data size in the KB. I&#39;m one of those stone age assembly / C / C++ low level driver / firmware guys that didn&#39;t &quot;keep up with the advanced technologies&quot;.<br /><br />One of the biggest problem I&#39;ve seen in mobile and battery powered system is that people write apps without consider the consequences of their works&#39; foot print. You can have GB of RAM and if your app isn&#39;t developed correctly, waste all of it. <br /><br />I agree, that it is tedious having to worry about how much memory I&#39;m consuming and repeating a bunch of set/get/init code for every module, but as a developer, it is <b>my</b> job to keep track of what and how much resource, at least in terms of ball park figure, without exceeding the GC&#39;s performance limit.<br /><br />You think GC is all wonderful and will solve the world&#39;s problem? Wait till you realized all of your extra resources provided by GC is consumed by a lazy app developer that can&#39;t keep track of how much resource he/she consumed.<br /><br />By the way, why messages instead of subclasses? I think it is because you can handle multiple cores better with messages and in the low level switches between tasks easier than having to check across each base/derive class to see when is a good time to switch between tasks. I&#39;m no Java developer, but I think it would be easier for the lower level (OS / task scheduler / power management / etc) to know the timing.<br /><br />This is a phone, and it runs on battery, so it is important to be a bit stingy and know the resource (memory, processing cycle, latency) at each point in time of the app&#39;s execution.<br /><br />-Shing
</p>
</dd>
